<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="Special-Statements" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Special Statements</title>


<definition xml:id="def-">
    <statement>
        <p> The <term>origin</term> in the Cartesian plane is the point <m>(0,0)</m>.
        </p>
    </statement>
</definition>

<p>
   And now we can use the axiom format. 
</p>

<axiom xml:id="axiom-">
    <statement>
        <p> The <term>origin</term> in the Cartesian plane is the point <m>(0,0)</m>.
        </p>
    </statement>
</axiom>

<p>
   And now we can write lots of lemmas.
</p>

<lemma xml:id="lem-sum-of-odd-numbers">
    <statement>
        <p> If <m> x</m> and <m>y</m> are odd, then <m>x+y</m> is not odd.
        </p>
    </statement>
    <proof>
        <p>
            Write <m>x = 2k+1</m> and <m>y = 2m+1</m>. Then <me>x + y = 2k+1 + 2m + 1 = 2k+2m +2</me>. Thus, <m>x +y</m> is divisible by 2, and is even.
        </p>
    </proof>
</lemma>

<p>
    And now we can experiment with referencing lemmas.
</p>

<theorem xml:id="thm-sum-of-four">
    <statement>
        <p> The sum of four odd numbers is even.
            
        </p>
    </statement>
    <proof>
        <p>
            Suppose <m>w,x,y,</m> and <m>z</m> are odd. 
            By <xref ref="lem-sum-of-odd-numbers"/>  we know that <m>x+y</m> and <m>w+z</m> are both even.
            But the sum of two even numbers is also even.
        </p>
    </proof>
</theorem>

</section>